<section id="platforms-wide-section">
    <!-- Main Title with Theme Colors -->
    <h2 class="platforms-main-title">PROJECTS & <span class="highlight-platforms">PLATFORMS</span></h2>

    <!-- Vertical Container for the Stacked Cards -->
    <div class="platforms-vertical-container">
        
        <div class="platform-card-wide">
            <h3 class="platform-title">Student Resource & Academic Support Hub</h3>
            <p class="platform-desc-text">The Student Resource & Academic Support Hub now features the comprehensive COS Student Survival Guide: a centralized sheet detailing everything you need to know about shifting, grievance procedures, enlistment, and essential department contacts. Everything you need to survive the semester, in one place and free. The grade calculator tells scholars exactly what they need to keep their funding. The academic pathing tool shows you what happens if you fail a subject and gives you a way forward. The syllabus portal, flashcard library, research job board, funding portal, free software directory, LaTeX guide, and NMAT repository are all there from day one. No paywalls. No runaround.</p>
        </div>
    
        <div class="platform-card-wide">
            <h3 class="platform-title">Transparency & Accountability Platform </h3>
            <p class="platform-desc-text">I hold myself to the same standard I ask of the administration. The grievance channel lets you report unfair grading privately, with the council mediating directly. The financial ledger posts every expenditure over ₱500 within 72 hours with the name of whoever approved it. The student rights charter tells you exactly what you can ask for. And the suggestion tab means any idea you post gets a real reply, not silence. </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Platform Card 3 -->
        <div class="platform-card-wide">
            <h3 class="platform-title">Inclusion, Accessibility & Representation Initiative </h3>
            <p class="platform-desc-text">Science spaces should actually work for everyone in them. We're running formal Filipino Sign Language training so our Deaf peers stop being an afterthought in our own labs. We're doing a student-led audit of every laboratory for physical barriers and submitting a formal report to the administration with a stated response deadline. And we're building a public archive of what women and minority graduates from this college have already achieved, proof, not just encouragement.</p>
        </div>

         <div class="platform-card-wide">
            <h3 class="platform-title">Queer & Trans Identity Education Series </h3>
            <p class="platform-desc-text">Queer and trans Filipinos have always existed here. Science and history both confirm it. The Queer Identity Science Forum brings in credentialed academics to ground our identities in real biology, psychology, and sociology. The Pre-Colonial Gender & Trans History session covers the Babaylan and the gender diversity that existed long before colonization erased it. Shanghay Laya is a website collecting queer and trans resources, therapy, hormone access, trusted news,  with a legally reviewed disclaimer and no grey-market links.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="platform-card-wide">
            <h3 class="platform-title"> Student Emergency Response & Relief Program </h3>
            <p class="platform-desc-text">This is where the actual money goes. The COS Pantry gives any student facing hunger immediate, no-questions-asked access to rice and canned goods. The Emergency Micro-Grant Fund releases money fast personal emergencies such as for commuting and food, and another pooled during a declared calamity, triggered by PAGASA bulletins or official LGU declarations, not council debate. The Welfare Outreach Registry lets you opt in for priority outreach during disasters. Your data is officer-only and wiped at the end of the term, so that we may come to you when an emergency comes.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="platform-card-wide">
            <h3 class="platform-title">Student Financial Empowerment Initiative </h3>
            <p class="platform-desc-text">The hidden costs of a science degree are real, and it's on us to do something about them. <strong>The Equipment & Apparel Exchange</strong> lets graduating students pass down lab gowns, calculators, and tools to those who need them, every item checked before listing, no implied warranty. <strong> Freelancing & Part-Time Work Seminar</strong>covers how to make real income as a student without defaulting to abusive work that does not pay enough. If you can't attend live, it's recorded and permanently on the Hub within 48 hours.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="platform-card-wide">
            <h3 class="platform-title">Fundraising & Local Business Collaboration Initiative</h3>
            <p class="platform-desc-text">These programs need actual funding and here's exactly where it comes from. This initiative partners with local businesses near campus, 3 to 5 partners per term, with a fixed split: 70% of proceeds go to the Emergency Fund, 30% to Research Grants, all tracked publicly on the Transparency Ledger. If no partners are secured in a given term, we don't go quiet about it. We acknowledge the gap publicly and immediately run a crowdfunding drive so the relief funds never hit zero.</p>
        </div>

    </div>
</section>
